{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2012}} [[File:Charles Robert Leslie - Sir Walter Scott - Ravenswood and Lucy at the Mermaiden's Well - Bride of Lammermoor.jpg|thumb|200px|A scene from ''[[The Bride of Lammermoor]]'']] '''Tales of my Landlord''' is a series of novels by Sir [[Walter Scott]] (1771–1832) that form a subset of the so-called [[Waverley Novels]]. There are four series:
{| class="wikitable" ! Title !! Published !! Main setting !! Period |- |colspan=4|''Tales of My Landlord'', 1st series: |- |&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Black Dwarf (novel)|The Black Dwarf]]'' || 1816 || [[Scottish Borders]] || 1707 |- |&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Tale of Old Mortality]]'' || 1816 || Southern Scotland || 1679–89 |- |colspan=4|''Tales of my Landlord'', 2nd series: |- |&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Heart of Midlothian]]'' || 1818 || [[Edinburgh]], [[Richmond, London]], || 1736 |- |colspan=4|''Tales of my Landlord'', 3rd series: |- |&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[The Bride of Lammermoor]]'' || 1819 || [[East Lothian]] || 1709–11 |- |&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[A Legend of Montrose]]'' || 1819 || [[Scottish Highlands]] || 1644–5 |- |colspan=4|''Tales of my Landlord'', 4th series: |- |&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[Count Robert of Paris]]'' || 1832 || [[Constantinople]], [[Shkodër|Scutari]] || 1097 |- |&nbsp;&nbsp;''[[Castle Dangerous]]'' || 1832 || [[Kirkcudbrightshire]] || 1307 |}
Of these, ''The Heart of Midlothian'' and ''The Bride of Lammermoor'' have been the most successful, and ''Old Mortality'' is considered by modern critics to be among Scott's best work. The fourth were the least successful.
They were so called because they were supposed to be tales collected from the (fictional) landlord of the Wallace Inn at Gandercleugh, compiled by a "Peter Pattieson", and edited and sent to the publisher by [[Jedediah Cleishbotham]]. This is gone into in great depth in the introduction to ''The Black Dwarf''.
The first series was planned to comprise four volumes, each containing a separate novel, but Scott — by his own admission — botched ''The Black Dwarf'', and ''Old Mortality'' came to be three volumes in its own right. [http://www.walterscott.lib.ed.ac.uk/works/novels/dwarf.html]. The other three series thus consisted of two volumes each, or just one, in the case of the second.
They were supposed to reflect aspects of Scottish regional life.
==See also== {{portal|Novels}} * [[Waverley Novels]]
